In
{part
(b)} we found that the other two eigenvalues $\lambda_2$ and $\lambda_3$
were complex conjugates, $1\pm{}i$. Therefore, the eigenvectors for
$\lambda_2$ and $\lambda_3$ will also occur in complex conjugate pairs.
It is then sufficient to just find one of the vectors and then conjugate
it to find the other. We will solve the vector for $\lambda_2=1+i$. This
means we are seeking a vector for which
(A-$\lambda_2$I)\textbf{x}=\textbf{0}.

\begin{align*}
A-\lambda_2I=A-(1+i)I=
\begin{bmatrix}
2-i  &  1  &  -3\\
-1  &  -1-i  &  2\\
1  &  0  &  -1-i
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

If we denote the vector \textbf{x} as {[}a,b,c{]} then we need to solve

\begin{align*}
\begin{bmatrix}
2-i  &  1  &  -3\\
-1  &  -1-i  &  2\\
1  &  0  &  -1-i
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
a\\
b\\
c
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
0\\
0\\
0
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

which is equivalent to solving

\begin{align*}
(2-i)a+b-3c&=0,\\
-a+(-1-i)b+2c&=0,\\
a+(-1-i)c=0.
\end{align*}

If we solve this we get a=(1+i)c and b=-ic for arbitrary c. We can set
c=1 without loss of generality to get that the eigenvector for
$\lambda_2$ is

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{x}_2=
\begin{bmatrix}
1+i\\
-i\\
1
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

This means automatically that the eigenvector for $\lambda_3$ is just
the conjugate of the eigenvector for $\lambda_2$. Therefore,

\begin{align*}
\mathbf{x}_3=\overline{\mathbf{x}_2}=
\begin{bmatrix}
1-i\\
i\\
1
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

\emph{If you still have trouble computing eigenvectors, it is a
worthwhile exercise to actually compute $\mathbf{x}_3$ using the method
above and comparing with this result.}
